<TITLE> Symonds vows to skip Pakistan tour </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 SYDNEY, Feb 20 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Australia all-rounder Andrew Symonds says he is planning to stand by his earlier decision to boycott any tours of Pakistan. Symonds said he remained concerned about security in Pakistan and was not prepared to tour the country, even if Australia agreed to an abbreviated tour. Pakistan officials have agreed to shorten Australia's scheduled visit from 48 days to 30 to ensure it goes ahead. They have also offered to provide unprecedented protection for all the Australian players but Symonds says he still does not want to go. "I don't think I would go," he told Australian television on Wednesday. "I just dread to think what would happen if someone got hurt, let alone killed. "It's just a situation you'd never want to find yourself in." Australian media have speculated that up to half the Australian team may boycott the tour if it goes ahead but officials said no decisions had been made. Australian and Pakistan board officials discussed earlier this week a shortened tour, which is now tentatively scheduled from March 29 and April 2
